==Life and career==
Reuter was born as '''Israel Beer Josaphat''' in [[Kassel]], Germany.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/luminary/von-reuter-paul-julius-baron|title=Heroes – Trailblazers of the Jewish People|last=|first=|date=|website=Beit Hatfutsot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}&lt;/ref&gt; His father, Samuel Levi Josaphat, was a [[rabbi]]. His mother was Betty Sanders. In [[Göttingen]], Reuter met [[Carl Friedrich Gauss]], who was experimenting with the [[transmission (telecommunications)|transmission]] of [[electric]]al signals via wire.{{cn|date=July 2020}}

On 29 October 1845, he moved to [[London]], calling himself Julius Josaphat. On 16 November 1845, he converted to [[Christianity]] in a ceremony at [[St George's German Lutheran Church|St. George's German Lutheran Chapel]] in London,&lt;ref name= &quot;encyclopedia.com&quot; /&gt; and changed his name to Paul Julius Reuter. One week later, in the same chapel, he married Ida Maria Elizabeth Clementine Magnus of [[Berlin]], daughter of a German banker.{{cn|date=July 2020}}

A former bank clerk, in 1847 he became a partner in Reuter and [[Joseph Abraham Stargardt|Stargardt]], a Berlin book-publishing firm. The distribution of radical pamphlets by the firm at the beginning of the [[Revolutions of 1848|1848 Revolution]] may have focused official scrutiny on Reuter. Later that year, he left for Paris&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation | url = https://www.britannica.com/biography/Paul-Julius-Freiherr-von-Reuter | title = Paul Julius, baron von Reuter | encyclopedia = Encyclopædia Britannica | year = 1998}}.&lt;/ref&gt; and worked in [[Charles-Louis Havas]]' news agency, [[Havas|Agence Havas]], the future [[Agence France Presse]].{{cn|date=July 2020}}

As [[telegraphy]] evolved, Reuter founded his own news agency in [[Aachen]], transferring messages between [[Brussels]] and Aachen using [[carrier pigeon]]s and thus linking [[Berlin]] and [[Paris]]. Speedier than the post train, pigeons gave Reuter faster access to financial news from the Paris stock exchange.  Eventually, pigeons were replaced by a direct telegraph link.&lt;ref&gt;Standage, T. ''The Victorian Internet'' (1999)&lt;/ref&gt;

A telegraph line was under construction between [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[Europe]], and so Reuter moved to London, renting an office near the [[London Stock Exchange|Stock Exchange]].  In 1863, he privately erected a telegraph link to [[Crookhaven]], the farthest south-west point of [[Ireland]]. On nearing Crookhaven, ships from [[United States|America]] threw canisters containing news into the sea. These were retrieved by Reuters and telegraphed directly to London, arriving long before the ships reached Cork.{{cn|date=July 2020}}

In 1872, [[Nasir al-Din Shah]], the Shah of [[Qajar dynasty|Iran]], signed an agreement with Reuter, a [[Reuter concession|concession]] selling him all railroads, canals, most of the mines, all the government's forests, and all future industries of Iran. [[George Curzon, 1st Marquess Curzon of Kedleston|George Curzon]] called it &quot;The most complete and extraordinary surrender of the entire industrial resources of a kingdom into foreign hands that has ever been dreamed of&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;''Persia and the Persian question'', Vol. I, London, Frank Cass and Co., 1966, p. 480.&lt;/ref&gt; The Reuter concession was immediately denounced by all ranks of businessmen, clergy, and nationalists of Persia, and it was quickly forced into cancellation.{{cn|date=July 2020}}

On 17 March 1857, Reuter was naturalised as a British subject. On 7 September 1871, the [[Ernest II, Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]] granted him the noble title of ''[[Freiherr]]'' (Baron).&lt;ref name=LG /&gt; In November 1891, [[Queen Victoria]] granted him (and his subsequent male-line successors) the right to use that German title (listed as &quot;Baron von Reuter&quot;) in Britain.&lt;ref name=LG /&gt;&lt;ref name= &quot;reuters.com&quot;&gt;{{Citation | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSTRE50O1GV20090125?feedType=RSS&amp;feedName=topNews | title = Baroness Reuter, last link to news dynasty, dies | publisher = Reuters | date = 25 January 2009}}.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Marriage and children==
In 1845, Reuter married Ida Maria Magnus, daughter of Friedrich Martin Magnus, a German banker in Berlin.&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0017_0_16674.html Paul Julius Freiherr von Reuter], Encyclopaedia Judaica, 2008, The Gale Group.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Lüders, Carsten, [https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/gnd137908784.html#ndbcontent &quot;Magnus, Friedrich Martin Freiherr von&quot;] in: Neue Deutsche Biographie 15 (1987), S. 672.&lt;/ref&gt; They had three sons: [[Herbert de Reuter|Herbert]], who became the 2nd Baron (succeeded by his son Hubert as 3rd Baron), George and Alfred.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|author=Jones, Sir Roderick|title=A life in Reuters|publisher=Hodder &amp; Stoughton |year=1951 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UAIdAQAAMAAJ}} The 2nd Baron (born 1852, died 1915) committed suicide 3 days after the death of his wife. He was succeeded by his son, Hubert.&lt;/ref&gt; Clementine Maria, one of his daughters, married Count {{ill|Otto Stenbock (diplomat)|sv|Otto Stenbock|lt=Otto Stenbock}}, and after Stenbock's death, Sir [[Herbert Chermside]], a [[Governors of Queensland|governor of Queensland]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chermside-sir-herbert-charles-5575|title=Australian Dictionary of Biography|first=Paul D.|last=Wilson|chapter=Chermside, Sir Herbert Charles (1850–1929)|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|via=Australian Dictionary of Biography}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The 2nd Baron's brother George had two sons, Oliver (who became the 4th Baron) and Ronald. The last member of the family, [[Marguerite, Baroness de Reuter]], widow of the 4th Baron and Paul Julius Reuter's granddaughter-in-law, died on 25 January 2009, at the age of 96.&lt;ref name=&quot;reuters.com&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=abc&gt;{{cite news|title=Baroness de Reuter, last link to news dynasty, dies |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/01/26/2474298.htm |agency=[[Reuters]]|work=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=26 January 2009|accessdate=21 February 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Death and commemoration==
Reuter died in 1899 at [[Villa Reuter]] in [[Nice]], [[French Third Republic|France]]. He was buried in [[West Norwood Cemetery]] in south London.{{cn|date=July 2020}}

Reuter was portrayed by [[Edward G. Robinson]] in the [[Warner Bros.]] biographical film ''[[A Dispatch from Reuters]]'' (1941).{{cn|date=July 2020}}

The Reuters News Agency commemorated the 100th anniversary of the death of its founder by launching a university award (the Paul Julius Reuter Innovation Award) in Germany.&lt;ref name=&quot;encyclopedia.com&quot;/&gt;

