'''Haile Selassie I''' ({{lang-gez |ቀዳማዊ ኃይለ ሥላሴ|Qädamawi Haylä Səllasé}},{{refn |Translates to &quot;Power of the Trinity&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[[Henry Louis Gates|Gates, Henry Louis]], and [[Kwame Anthony Appiah|Anthony Appiah]], ''Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience''. 1999, p. 902.&lt;/ref&gt; |group= nb}} {{IPA-am|ˈhaɪlə sɨlˈlase|-|Haile Selassie.ogg}};{{refn|{{IPAc-en|lang|ˈ|h|aɪ|l|i|_|s|ə|ˈ|l|æ|s|i|,_|-|ˈ|l|ɑː|s|i}}&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation | url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/cgi-bin/audio.pl?bixhai02.wav=Haile+Selassie | title = Haile Selassie | work = Merriam-webster | accessdate = 24 April 2014|mode=cs1}}.; {{Citation | url = http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/haile+selassie | title = Haile Selassie | work = Dictionary | publisher = Reference | accessdate = 24 April 2014|mode=cs1}}.&lt;/ref&gt;|group= nb}} born '''[[Ethiopian aristocratic and court titles#Men's honorifics|Lij]]''' '''Tafari Makonnen'''; 23 July 1892{{spnd}}27 August 1975)&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |title= Colonialism: an international, social, cultural, and political encyclopedia |volume= 1| last1 = Page | first1 = Melvin Eugene |last2 = Sonnenburg | first2 = Penny M. |page= 247 |publisher= ABC-CLIO |year= 2003 |isbn= 978-1-57607-335-3 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qFTHBoRvQbsC&amp;pg=PA247 }}&lt;/ref&gt; was the [[Emperor|Emperor of Ethiopia]] from 1930 to 1974. Prior his coronation, he had been the [[Ethiopian aristocratic and court titles|Regent Plenipotentiary of Ethiopia]] from 1916. He is a defining figure in modern Ethiopian history.&lt;ref&gt;Erlich, Haggai (2002), ''The Cross and the River: Ethiopia, Egypt, and the Nile''.  Lynne Rienner Publishers.  {{ISBN|1-55587970-5}}, p. 192.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name= babylon148&gt;{{Harvnb |Murrell | p = 148}}&lt;/ref&gt; He was a member of the [[Solomonic dynasty]] who traced his lineage to Emperor [[Menelik I]].

Selassie attempted to modernize the country through a series of [[Modernization under Haile Selassie|political and social reforms]], including the introduction of Ethiopia's [[1931 Constitution of Ethiopia|first written constitution]] and the abolition of slavery. He led the failed efforts to defend Ethiopia during the [[Second Italo-Ethiopian War]] and spent the period of [[Italian East Africa|Italian occupation]] in exile in England. He returned to lead Ethiopia in 1941 after the British Empire defeated the Italian occupiers in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African campaign]]. He dissolved the [[Federation of Ethiopia and Eritrea]], which was established by the UN General Assembly in 1950, and integrated Eritrea as a province of Ethiopia while [[Eritrean War of Independence|fighting to prevent their independence]]. 

His internationalist views led to Ethiopia becoming a charter member of the United Nations.&lt;ref&gt;Karsh, Efraim (1988), ''Neutrality and Small States''. Routledge. {{ISBN|0-41500507-8}}, p. 112.&lt;/ref&gt; In 1963, he presided over the formation of the [[Organisation of African Unity]], the precursor of the [[African Union]], and served as its first chairman. He was overthrown in a 1974 military coup by a [[Soviet Union]]-backed [[Derg|junta]] and was murdered by the junta on 27 August 1975.
